I"D
<p>Just came across this on <a href="http://news.ycombinator.com/">HN</a> and it looks incredibly exciting - a feature in the upcoming version of Photoshop that allows you to fill spaces seamlessly and intelligently.  The video highlights using it for removing unwanted artifacts (instead of using the spot healing tool) and patching large chunks of an image.  It looks like it can be a bit CPU intensive when calculating larger areas, however achieving the same effect manually would take much, much longer.</p>

<object width="600" height="475"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/NH0aEp1oDOI&#038;hl=en_US&#038;fs=1&#038;rel=0" />&lt;/param&gt;<param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" />&lt;/param&gt;<param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" />&lt;/param&gt;<embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/NH0aEp1oDOI&#038;hl=en_US&#038;fs=1&#038;rel=0" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="600" height="475" />&lt;/embed&gt;</object>

<p>Of note, this immediately brought back memories of <a href="http://www.cs.princeton.edu/gfx/pubs/Barnes_2009_PAR/index.php">PatchMatch</a>, a patching algorithm created by researchers from Princeton and <a href="http://www.adobe.com/technology/people/seattle/shechtman.html">Adobe Advanced Technology Labs</a>.  Check out the video below:</p>

<object width="600" height="450"><param name="allowfullscreen" value="true" /><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><param name="movie" value="http://vimeo.com/moogaloop.swf?clip_id=5024379&amp;server=vimeo.com&amp;show_title=1&amp;show_byline=1&amp;show_portrait=0&amp;color=00ADEF&amp;fullscreen=1" /><embed src="http://vimeo.com/moogaloop.swf?clip_id=5024379&amp;server=vimeo.com&amp;show_title=1&amp;show_byline=1&amp;show_portrait=0&amp;color=00ADEF&amp;fullscreen=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowfullscreen="true" allowscriptaccess="always" width="600" height="450" />&lt;/embed&gt;</object>

